{"build_type":"library","description":"Dynamic kernel memory grant, LOCK-FREE (Slice 1). Hands one 16-byte-aligned chunk out of the kernel-managed pool by a single wait-free atomic_fetch_add on the pool cursor CELL at g_kernel_pool_base+768 (atomics need a computed address; the cursor cannot be a bare global). If the post-bump frontier passes the pool end cell at g_kernel_pool_base+776 it retracts its own delta (give-back) and returns zero, so the caller parks on a memory-available event instead of OOM. Concurrent overshooters each retract independently, so the bump is linearizable with no lock and no CAS. Returns the old cursor (chunk base), or zero on exhaustion. The single door allocate-system-memory-chunk-region routes here only once armed (g_kernel_pool_end != 0); until then this is dormant. Before the atomic cursor bump it first tries the shared lock-free reclaim ring for the request's size class (slab at g_kernel_pool_base+832): a hit returns a reused chunk with no bump; a miss falls through to the wait-free atomic_fetch_add bump exactly as before. This is what makes freed worker memory reusable cross-thread and cross-reconcile without the cursor ever retreating.","module_name":"grant-chunk-within-kernel-managed-region","package_name":"grant-chunk-within-kernel-managed-region","function_definitions":{"grant-chunk-within-kernel-managed-region":{"return_type":"i64","parameter_definitions":[{"parameter_name":"len","parameter_type":"i64"}],"execution_instructions":[{"instruction_type":"variable_declaration","variable_name":"zero","variable_type":"i64","assignment_operation":"literal","source_target":0},{"instruction_type":"variable_declaration","variable_name":"fifteen","variable_type":"i64","assignment_operation":"literal","source_target":15},{"instruction_type":"variable_declaration","variable_name":"mask","variable_type":"i64","assignment_operation":"literal","source_target":-16},{"instruction_type":"variable_declaration","variable_name":"c768","variable_type"